Use **`WebApplicationFactory<T>`** from `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing`. It hosts your entire ASP.NET Core pipeline in-memory — no real ports, no real server — and gives you an `HttpClient` wired directly into it.

### Setup

```bash
dotnet add package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
```

### Example test

```csharp
public class McpIntegrationTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly HttpClient _client;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _client = factory.CreateClient();
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task Initialize_ReturnsCapabilities()
    {
        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 1,
            method = "initialize",
            @params = new
            {
                protocolVersion = "2025-03-26",
                capabilities = new { },
                clientInfo = new { name = "test-client", version = "1.0" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.Equal("2.0", body.GetProperty("jsonrpc").GetString());
        Assert.Equal(1, body.GetProperty("id").GetInt32());
        Assert.True(body.GetProperty("result").TryGetProperty("capabilities", out _));
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ToolsCall_ExecutesTool()
    {
        // Initialize first (MCP requires it)
        await InitializeSession();

        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 2,
            method = "tools/call",
            @params = new
            {
                name = "my_tool",
                arguments = new { input = "hello" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        var content = body.GetProperty("result").GetProperty("content");
        Assert.False(content.EnumerateArray().First()
            .TryGetProperty("isError", out _));
    }

    private async Task InitializeSession() { /* send initialize as above */ }
}
```

### Key points

| Concern | Approach |
|---|---|
| **No real server** | `WebApplicationFactory` hosts in-process |
| **Override services** | Use `factory.WithWebHostBuilder(b => b.ConfigureServices(...))` to swap in mocks (e.g., fake DB) |
| **SSE transport** | Read the response stream with `ReadAsStreamAsync()` and parse `text/event-stream` lines |
| **Session state** | Reuse the same `HttpClient` instance across calls to preserve cookies/headers |
| **Auth** | Configure a test auth handler via `AddAuthentication("Test")` in the service overrides |

### If you use SSE (Streamable HTTP)

```csharp
var request = new HttpRequestMessage(HttpMethod.Post, "/mcp");
request.Headers.Accept.Add(new("text/event-stream"));
request.Content = JsonContent.Create(initializePayload);

var response = await _client.SendAsync(request,
    HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead);

using var stream = await response.Content.ReadAsStreamAsync();
using var reader = new StreamReader(stream);

while (await reader.ReadLineAsync() is { } line)
{
    if (line.StartsWith("data: "))
    {
        var json = JsonDocument.Parse(line[6..]);
        // assert on each SSE event
    }
}
```

This gives you full protocol-level coverage (JSON-RPC framing, content negotiation, session lifecycle) with the speed of an in-process call.
